{#
  Example 01 — The default control: an icon button that opens a
  listbox.

  The simplest possible mount. The trigger button shows a globe glyph
  (U+1F310), and opening it reveals a <ul role="listbox"> with one
  <li role="option"> per locale. Each option renders its locale's
  pretty name (from the `localeLabels` opt; falls back to the bare
  code) and its own `lang="…"` so screen readers pronounce each in
  the right language.

  Outcome: a collapsed button. Enter / Space / ArrowDown opens the
  listbox; Enter, Space, or a click commits, which writes
  `<html lang="…" dir="…">`, fills the hidden input, and fires
  `onChange`.

  Note the status region below the control. The closed button shows
  only the glyph, never the active locale, so a screen-reader user
  would otherwise have no way to hear which locale is active. The
  status line is part of the default pattern — see
  ../docs/accessibility.md. Omitting it is the deliberate choice.

  Note also that none of this works before locale-chooser.client.js
  loads: the button opens nothing without JS. The hidden input is
  pre-filled server-side, so a no-JS form submit still carries a
  locale, but that is the only unenhanced affordance. See
  ../docs/ssr.md.
#}
{% from "../locale-chooser.njk" import localeChooser %}

{{ localeChooser({
    label: "Choose your language",
    locales: ["en", "fr", "ar"],
    localeLabels: { en: "English", fr: "Français", ar: "العربية" },
    value: "en"
}) }}

{#
  Visible by default: it helps sighted users and cognitive
  accessibility too, and WCAG 2.2 AAA favours it. For designs that
  cannot spare the space, make it visually hidden instead of dropping
  it — recipe in ../docs/styling.md.

  aria-live="polite" announces mutations only, so this region is
  silent on first paint and speaks on each subsequent change. That is
  the intended behaviour.
#}
<p class="locale-chooser-status" aria-live="polite"></p>

<script type="module">
    import { autoInit, localeName } from "../locale-chooser.client.js";

    const status = document.querySelector(".locale-chooser-status");

    autoInit({
        onChange(code) {
            // localeName() resolves the human name from the built-in
            // table ("en_US" -> "English (United States)"), so the
            // region shows a real language name, not a raw code.
            status.textContent = `Active language: ${localeName(code)}`;
        },
    });
</script>
